  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- First laws requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Limited scope and enforcement\n\n2. International Developments\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Developed comprehensive recommendations for countries\n\n3. Key Legislation\n- 1990s: Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Expanded definitions of financial crimes\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Broader international cooperation\n\n4. Post-9/11 Changes\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Stronger regulations targeting terrorist financing\n- More stringent customer identification protocols\n- Increased information sharing between agencies\n\n5. Recent Developments\n- Digital currency regulations\n- Enhanced cybercrime prevention\n- Stricter beneficial ownership transparency\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n\n6. Global Trends\n- Comprehensive risk-based approaches\n- Increased regulatory complexity\n- More sophisticated detection mechanisms\n- Continuous adaptation to emerging financial technologies\n\nThese legislative progressions reflect growing sophistication in addressing complex financial criminal activities.",
